XRD was usually used to detect the interlayer spacing between graphene layers, and the XRD spectra of the prepared GQDs composite membranes were shown in Fig. S7b and Fig. 6a. From Fig. S7b, three peaks at 17.8°, 22.7° and 26.0° were the feature diffraction peaks of PSF substrate membrane [54], and no obvious diffraction peak at 2θ = 5–16° was found in the XRD pattern of M1 membrane, indicating the disordered stacking of GQDs nanosheets in the M1 membrane [55]. This indicated that M1 membrane did not have the typical interlayer spacing structure commonly detected in GO laminar membrane, which was consistent with our previous study [42]. Fig. 6
                        a showed the XRD spectra of the post-crosslinked GQDs composite membranes, only M1C and M2C had a low-intensity diffraction peak at 2θ = 8.6° corresponding to a GQDs nanosheets interlayer spacing of 1.028 nm, indicating the existence of part parallel stacking in disordered stacked GQDs nanosheets in the post-crosslinked GQDs composite membranes (M1C and M2C) [56,57]. This might be closely related to the small diameter of GQDs nanosheets (average size: 2.39 nm) and the acylation reaction of peripheral carboxyl groups (Fig. 5a), leading to the polydispersity of GQDs nanosheets in both horizontal and vertical directions of the membrane, even though small diameter nanosheets might be beneficial to increase the number of vertical nanochannels in the horizontal direction and shorten the channel tortuosity in the vertical direction [5]. Therefore, we deduced that the covalent reactions of GQDs nanosheets with diamine monomers were occurred simultaneously between parallel and perpendicular GQDs nanosheets in the membrane preparation process (Fig. 7
                        ).
